<body>
<a class="skip-link" href="#main-content">Skip to main content</a>
<header>
<h1>Sued by Credit Card Company?</h1>
<p class="subtitle">Don't Panic. Here's Exactly What to Do.</p>
</header>
<div class="container">
<main id="main-content">
<div class="content-section">
<h2>You Just Got Served - Now What?</h2>
<p>Take a breath. Being sued by a credit card company is stressful but it is not an emergency that requires immediate action beyond one thing: note the deadline to respond. You typically have 20-30 days (varies by state) to file an answer with the court. Missing this deadline results in a <a href="https://defaultjudgment.org/" title="default judgment">default judgment</a>.</p>
</div>
<div class="content-section">
<h2>Step 1: Read the Complaint Carefully</h2>
<p>The complaint will state: who is suing you (original creditor or debt buyer), the amount claimed, the account number, and the legal basis. Check every detail. Is the amount correct? Is this actually your account? Has the statute of limitations expired? <a href="https://debtstatuteoflimitations.com">Check your state's statute of limitations</a>.</p>
</div>
<div class="content-section">
<h2>Step 2: File an Answer</h2>
<p>Even if you owe the money, file an answer. Respond to each paragraph: admit, deny, or state you lack sufficient information. Raise affirmative defenses: statute of limitations, lack of standing (if sued by debt buyer), improper service, incorrect amount.</p>
<p>Many courts have fill-in-the-blank answer forms. Check your local court website.</p>
</div>
<div class="content-section">
<h2>Step 3: Request Validation</h2>
<p>If a debt buyer is suing you (not the original creditor), demand they prove they own the debt. They must produce the original credit agreement, a complete chain of ownership, and an accounting of every charge and payment. Many debt buyers cannot produce these documents. <a href="https://ceaseanddesistdebt.com">Cease and desist guide</a>.</p>
</div>
<div class="content-section">
<h2>Common Defenses</h2>
<p><strong>Statute of limitations:</strong> If the debt is time-barred, the lawsuit fails.</p>
<p><strong>Lack of standing:</strong> Debt buyers must prove they own the specific account.</p>
<p><strong>Wrong amount:</strong> Challenge interest, fees, and charges that were not in the original agreement.</p>
<p><strong>Identity:</strong> Sometimes the wrong person is sued.</p>
<p><strong>Already paid or settled:</strong> Bring proof of any payments or settlement agreements.</p>
</div>
<div class="content-section">
<h2>The Bankruptcy Option</h2>
<p>Filing bankruptcy immediately stops the lawsuit through the <a href="https://automaticstay.org" rel="noopener" target="_blank" title="Automatic Stay in Bankruptcy - Open Bankruptcy Project">automatic stay</a>. If you have multiple debts and this lawsuit is just one problem among many, bankruptcy may be the most efficient solution. <a href="https://whatischapter7.com/" title="Chapter 7">Chapter 7</a> eliminates the <a href="https://creditcarddebtbankruptcy.org" rel="noopener" target="_blank" title="Credit Card Debt and Bankruptcy - Open Bankruptcy Project">credit card debt</a> entirely. <a href="https://automaticstay.org">The automatic stay explained</a>.</p>
<p><a href="https://howmuchdoesbankruptcycost.com">How much does bankruptcy cost?</a></p>
</div>
<div class="content-section">
<h2>What Happens If You Lose</h2>
<p>If a judgment is entered against you, the creditor can garnish wages (up to 25% of disposable income), levy bank accounts, and place liens on property. Bankruptcy can still eliminate judgment debt and stop <a href="https://stopgarnishment.org/" title="wage garnishment">garnishment</a> even after a judgment is entered. <a href="https://judgmentproof.org">Are you judgment proof?</a></p>
</div>
<div class="faq-section">
<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="faq-item">
<h3>How long do I have to respond to a credit card lawsuit?</h3>
<p>Typically 20-30 days from the date you are served, depending on your state. Check the summons for the exact deadline.</p>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<h3>Can I negotiate a settlement after being sued?</h3>
<p>Yes. Many creditors will settle for 40-60% of the balance even after filing suit. Get any agreement in writing before paying.</p>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<h3>What if I cannot afford a lawyer?</h3>
<p>Many legal aid organizations help with debt defense. You can also represent yourself (<a href="https://prosebankruptcy.org/" title="pro se">pro se</a>). The court clerk can provide answer forms.</p>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<h3>Will bankruptcy stop the lawsuit?</h3>
<p>Yes, immediately. The <a href="https://automaticstay.org" rel="noopener" target="_blank" title="Automatic Stay in Bankruptcy - Open Bankruptcy Project">automatic stay</a> halts all litigation the moment you file.</p>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<h3>What happens if a credit card company sues me?</h3>
<p>The credit card company or a debt buyer files a lawsuit seeking a money judgment. If you do not respond within 20-30 days, the court enters a <a href="https://defaultjudgment.org/" title="default judgment">default judgment</a> allowing <a href="https://garnishedwages.org" rel="noopener" target="_blank" title="Wage Garnishment and Bankruptcy - Open Bankruptcy Project">wage garnishment</a> up to 25% of disposable income, bank account levies, and property liens.</p>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<h3>Can they garnish my wages for credit card debt?</h3>
<p>Yes, but only after obtaining a court judgment. Credit card companies cannot garnish wages without suing you first and winning. After a judgment, federal law caps <a href="https://stopgarnishment.org/" title="wage garnishment">garnishment</a> at 25% of disposable earnings or the amount exceeding 30 times minimum wage, whichever is less.</p>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<h3>Should I file bankruptcy if I am being sued?</h3>
<p>Bankruptcy may be the best option if you have multiple debts, not just the one lawsuit. Filing immediately stops the suit through the <a href="https://automaticstay.org/" title="automatic stay">automatic stay</a>. <a href="https://whatischapter7.com/" title="Chapter 7">Chapter 7</a> eliminates <a href="https://creditcarddebtbankruptcy.org" rel="noopener" target="_blank" title="Credit Card Debt and Bankruptcy - Open Bankruptcy Project">credit card debt</a> entirely if you qualify under the <a href="https://meanstest.org" rel="noopener" target="_blank" title="Bankruptcy Means Test - Open Bankruptcy Project">means test</a>. Consult a bankruptcy attorney or use a free screener.</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cta-box">
<p>Check your bankruptcy <a href="https://bankruptcydischarge.org/" title="discharge">discharge</a> eligibility with our free screening tool.</p>
<a class="btn" href="https://1328f.com?utm_source=suedbycreditcardcompany.com&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_campaign=btn-network">Free Discharge Screener</a>
</div>
<div class="about-data">
<strong>About This Data:</strong> Content based on federal bankruptcy law (Title 11, U.S. Code)
    and the Fair Debt Collection Practices Act (15 U.S.C. 1692). District-level statistics from the
    <a href="https://www.fjc.gov/" rel="noopener" target="_blank">Federal Judicial Center</a> Integrated Database (37.9 million cases, 94 districts, FY 2008-2024).
    This is educational content, not legal advice.
  </div>
